Name: Hip-joint armchair
Material: walnut, elm, ivory, bone, pewter, silk velvet

Name: Coffin knob
Footnote: One end of this knob shows lotus flowers enhanced with geometric patterns and green leaves arranged symmetrically around a central disc in red. This iconography would be suitable for a funerary object, as the lotus is associated with the regeneration or rebirth of the deceased.

Name: Terracotta krater
Footnote: During the eighth century B.C., the Geometric style that had originated in Athens spread throughout the Greek-speaking world.

Name: Costume
Material: broadcloth, chintz, cotton, woollen and cotton thread

Name: Sampler
Footnote: In their earliest form, samplers were put together by embroiderers as personal reference works. They showed trials of patterns and stitches that had been copied from other embroideries.
